# Requirements

## Project Summary
**Resume**: A single-web page application that serves as a knowledge base for new **M**ining **S**oftware **R**epositories researchers.

## Stakeholders
- New PhD students joining the MSR research group.
- MSR researchers.

## Scope

- Single-page web application
- Simple html structure and styling
- Four categories:
    1. Data Sources
    2. Collection Methods
    3. Analysis Methods
    4. Publication Venues
- Tab switching
- Each tab displays structured content

## Functional Requirements

- The page must have a navigation area with four tabs
    1. Data Sources:
        - source name
        - what kind of data it provides
        - brief description
    2. Collection Methods:
        - method name
        - what it's used for
        - pros and cons
    3. Analysis Methods
        - method name
        - type of analysis
        - common use cases
    4. Publication Venues
        - vanue name and abbreviation
        - type (conference or journal)
        - focus area
        - how relevant to MSR (high, medium)
- The page must show one section/tab content at a time.
- Clicking a tab must update the visible content to the selected category.
- The page must clearly indicate the currently selected tab.

## Non-Functional Requirements

- The page must look clean and be readable.
- It must look professional but simple with no fancy animations.
- It must be compatible on all modern browsers.
- It must respond inmediately when switching tabs without reloading.
- The buttons/tabs must appear at the top.
- Table or list format.

## User Stories

1. **As a new PhD student**, I want to see available data sources, so I can choose which data to collect.

2. **As a new PhD student**, I want to see common collection and analysis methods with pros/cons, so I can choose a practical way to gather data.

3. **As a new PhD student**, I want to know different platforms where I can publish my work.

3. **As a researcher**, I want to view analysis methods and typical use cases, so I can select methods appropriate to my study.

4. **As a researcher**, I want to compare publication venues, so I can pick the most appropriate one.

5. **As a user**, I want the webpage to use simple tabs and show only one section at a time, so the content is not overwhelming.